<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-965-726  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 965 726.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 11 1989 n249 p40(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Defense fights the paper war; Army, Navy draw up battle plans tostore information electronically. (includes a related article onthe US Space Station Program's Technical and ManagementInformation System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Messmer, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A goal of the US Department of Defense's (DOD's) Computer-AidedAcquisition and Logistics Support (CALS) program was to implementa digital system of networks and optical imaging for technicaldesign and weapon systems data by 1990.andP;  The Navy CALS programwill use integrated databases for retrieving computer-aided designand computer-aided engineering (CAD/CAE) information; it hopes tomanufacture parts directly from the database.andP;  The Navy's RapidAcquisition of Manufactured Parts (Ramps) program has beenstudying robotic engineering with database input.andP;  The Army'sInformation Systems Selection and Acquisition Agency (ISSAA) hasawarded its first CALS contracts with the intent of developing anintegrated architecture able to address all weapons systems andseven functional areas.andP;  The contracts are comprised of fourphases and span 14 years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseUnited States. ArmyUnited States. NavyAutomationDigital CommunicationsImage ProcessingInformation Storage and RetrievalIntegrated SystemsData BasesGovernment AgencyOffice AutomationMilitaryPlanning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>